  "narrative": {
    "intro": "This ranking lists the leading federal contractors by obligations for FY2026 to date, with total obligations of $191B for the period. The list shows FISHER SAND & GRAVEL CO with $13.3B in obligations at the top, followed by TRIWEST HEALTHCARE ALLIANCE CORP with $12.6B and LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION with $10B. Other large contractors include MCKESSON CORPORATION at $9.9B, a second entry for LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $8.8B, and ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION at $8.3B. The ranking continues with OPTUM PUBLIC SECTOR SOLUTIONS, INC. at $6.6B, BARNARD CONSTRUCTION COMPANY, INCORPORATED at $5.9B, THE BOEING COMPANY at $5.8B, and TRIAD NATIONAL SECURITY, LLC at $5.1B. Total award value figures shown are full contract values, not single-year obligations, and the ranking orders contractors by the obligation amounts recorded in the FY2026 to date period. This presentation highlights which vendors account for the largest obligation totals within the reported $191B, and lists each contractor with its corresponding obligation figure for clarity and direct comparison.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Who are the top contractors by obligations in FY2026 to date?",
        "body": "The top contractors by obligations for FY2026 to date begin with FISHER SAND & GRAVEL CO at $13.3B, then TRIWEST HEALTHCARE ALLIANCE CORP at $12.6B, and LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $10B. The list also includes MCKESSON CORPORATION at $9.9B, LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION again at $8.8B, and ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION at $8.3B. Remaining positions in the top ten are OPTUM PUBLIC SECTOR SOLUTIONS, INC. at $6.6B, BARNARD CONSTRUCTION COMPANY, INCORPORATED at $5.9B, THE BOEING COMPANY at $5.8B, and TRIAD NATIONAL SECURITY, LLC at $5.1B."
      },
      {
        "heading": "What does the reported $191B total represent?",
        "body": "The reported $191B represents total obligations recorded for the FY2026 to date period. The note clarifies that total award value figures are full contract values, not single-year obligations, so the $191B reflects the sum of obligations in the reporting period rather than multi-year contract ceilings."
      }
    ]
